articles.author: Reuters
articles.description: WikiLeaks founder Julian Assange on Wednesday reached the Northern Mariana Islands, where he is expected to plead guilty to violating U.S. espionage law that will set him free and allow him return home to Australia.
articles.title: WikiLeaks' Assange arrives in Mariana Islands for US plea deal

articles.author: Aaron Ross, George Obulutsa
articles.description: Police opened fire on demonstrators trying to storm Kenya's legislature on Tuesday, with at least five protesters killed, dozens wounded and sections of the parliament building set ablaze as lawmakers inside passed legislation to raise taxes.
articles.title: Police open fire on demonstrators trying to storm Kenya parliament, several dead

articles.author: Nidal Al-Mughrabi
articles.description: Israeli forces killed at least 24 Palestinians in three separate airstrikes on Gaza City early on Tuesday, health officials said, while tanks deepened their incursion into the town of Rafah in the south of the enclave.
articles.title: Israeli airstrikes kill at least 24 in Gaza City, say Gaza officials

articles.author: Gram Slattery, Simon Lewis
articles.description: Two key advisers to Donald Trump have presented him with a plan to end Russia's war in Ukraine - if he wins the Nov. 5 presidential election - that involves telling Ukraine it will only get more U.S. weapons if it enters peace talks.
articles.title: Exclusive: Trump handed plan to halt US military aid to Kyiv unless it talks peace with Moscow

articles.author: Aidan Lewis
articles.description: Gaza remains at high risk of famine as war between Israel and Hamas continues and access to aid is restricted, though delivery of supplies had limited the projected spread of extreme hunger in northern areas, a global monitor said on Tuesday.
articles.title: High risk of famine persists across Gaza, global hunger monitor says

articles.author: Joyce Lee
articles.description: North Korea's launch of an unknown ballistic missile toward the sea off the east coast of the Korean Peninsula appears to have failed, South Korean military said on Wednesday.
articles.title: North Korea missile launch appears to have failed, South Korean military says

articles.author: Hyunsu Yim
articles.description: South Korean authorities on Wednesday ordered a lithium battery maker to halt factory operations indefinitely after a fire killed 23 people and said three company officials were under investigation on suspicion of having violated industrial safety laws.
articles.title: South Korean authorities order battery maker to halt operations over deadly blaze

articles.author: Reuters
articles.description: Reporters were briefly allowed to film U.S. journalist Evan Gershkovich on Wednesday before the start of his trial in the Russian city of Yekaterinburg on charges of espionage that he denies.
articles.title: Gershkovich appears with shaved head before start of closed trial in Russia

articles.author: Reuters
articles.description: Candidates in Friday's Iranian presidential election have vowed to revive the flagging economy, but voters see little prospect of relief from a cost of living squeeze without an end to sanctions and an easing of Iran's international isolation.
articles.title: Iran election hopefuls struggle to offer fix for economic woes

articles.author: Reuters
articles.description: Takeoff and landing at South Korea's Incheon international airport was disrupted on Wednesday for about three hours before dawn because of balloons launched by North Korea filled with refuse, an airport spokesperson said.
articles.title: Incheon airport briefly shuts down runways because of North Korea trash balloons
